    tool_output=ToolOutput(
        output='# Risk Factors and Cautions Disclosed in the SpaceX S-1\n\n## 1. Recast Financial Statements and Retrospective Combination\n\nThe S-1 discloses that the consolidated financial statements have been **retrospectively recast for all periods presented** to include:\n\n- The historical results of **X.AI Holdings Corp.**, acquired by SpaceX effective February 2, 2026 (the "xAI Merger")\n- The historical results of **X Holdings Corp.**, acquired by xAI effective March 28, 2025 (the "X Merger")\n- A **five-for-one forward stock split** of Class A, Class B, and Class C Common Stock, effective May 4, 2026 (the "2026 Stock Split")\n\nAll share and per share information has been **retroactively adjusted** to reflect the 2026 Stock Split for all periods presented.\n\n## 2. Caution That Historical Data May Not Predict Future Results\n\nThe prospectus explicitly cautions:\n\n> "The summary historical consolidated financial and operating data presented below is **not indicative of the results to be expected for any future period**, and the results for any interim period are not necessarily indicative of the results to be expected for the full fiscal period."\n\nThe summary historical data is also described as **"qualified in its entirety"** by the full consolidated financial statements and related notes, and is "not intended to replace" them.\n\n## 3. Change in Reporting Entity\n\nThe S-1 states that the presentation of the combined capital stock and shareholders\' equity—reflecting a continuation of historical SpaceX equity combined with the historical equity of X and xAI (as adjusted by exchange ratios)—**"constitutes a change in reporting entity."** Readers are directed to Note 12 (or Note 13 in an alternate reference) for additional details.\n\n## 4. Common-Control Accounting Treatment\n\nThe Mergers were accounted for as **reorganizations of entities under common control**, because Elon Musk had a controlling financial interest in SpaceX, xAI, and X through his majority voting interest in each entity during all periods presented. Key consequences include:\n\n- **Retrospective combination** of the net assets of the entities at their **historical carrying amounts** for all periods presented\n- **No new goodwill or other intangible assets** were recorded\n- All **historical related party transactions between the entities have been eliminated in consolidation**\n\n## 5. Lack of Standalone Financial Information for xAI and X\n\nThe S-1 explicitly states:\n\n> "As the consolidated financial statements already reflect the reorganization of entities under common control for all periods presented, **separate financial statements of xAI and X are not provided.**"\n\nThis means investors cannot independently evaluate the standalone historical financial performance, liquidity, or capital structure of xAI or X prior to their merger into SpaceX.\n\n## 6. Segment Reporting Limitations and Realignment\n\nFollowing the Mergers, the Company **re-evaluated its segment structure** and determined that, effective Q1 2026, the CODM (Chief Executive Officer) organizes the company into **three operating and reportable segments**: (i) Space, (ii) Connectivity, and (iii) AI. The S-1 notes:\n\n> "Prior period presentations for segments conform to the current segment reporting structure."\n\nThis means historical segment data has been **retroactively re-mapped** to the new three-segment structure, which may limit comparability to any prior segment disclosures made by xAI or X as standalone entities. The CODM evaluates segments based on **segment income (loss) from operations** by comparing actual results to historical results and previously forecasted financial information, and does not evaluate segments using [an unspecified alternative metric—likely assets or other measures].\n\n## 7. Risk Factor: AI Segment Integration and Operational Risks\n\nAmong the enumerated risk factors, the S-1 specifically calls out:\n\n> "The Company\'s **AI segment is recently formed, still being integrated**, operates in a rapidly evolving industry and is subject to **integration, execution, competitive and operational risks**."\n\nThis is a direct caution that the recast financials embed the results of a segment that is still being integrated and whose historical performance may not be indicative of future results.\n\n## 8. xAI Redeemable Convertible Preferred Stock Not Retrospectively Recast\n\nThe S-1 discloses an important **asymmetry** in the retrospective recasting:\n\n> "Because the xAI Redeemable Convertible Preferred Stock was legally outstanding during all historical periods prior to the xAI Merger and represented a separate equity class of a legally distinct predecessor entity, the conversion of xAI Redeemable Convertible Preferred Stock into SpaceX Common Stock is recognized **only as of the closing of the xAI Merger, and not retrospectively**."\n\nAccordingly, the historical consolidated balance sheets and statements of redeemable convertible preferred stock and shareholders\' equity **reflect the xAI Redeemable Convertible Preferred Stock as outstanding** (in its legal form) during those periods and are **not recast on an as-converted basis** for periods prior to the xAI Merger Date. This creates a discontinuity in the equity presentation across periods.\n\n## 9. Exchange Ratios Applied Retroactively\n\nThe S-1 details the conversion terms:\n\n| Security | Conversion Ratio |\n|---|---|\n| X Holdings Common Stock → xAI Common Stock (same class) | 2.776 shares (rounded down) |\n| X.AI Corp. Common Stock → xAI Common Stock (same class) | 1.000 share |\n| X.AI Corp. Preferred Stock → xAI Redeemable Convertible Preferred Stock | 1.000 share |\n\nAll shares of historical X, X.AI Corp., and xAI Common Stock are **presented as if converted into SpaceX Common Stock** at the applicable exchange rate for all periods presented through the xAI Merger Date. X.AI Corp. and xAI Redeemable Convertible Preferred Stock are presented at historical values with an adjustment to the conversion rate at the applicable exchange ratio per the xAI Merger.\n\n## 10. Related Party Transactions Eliminated in Consolidation\n\nThe S-1 states:\n\n> "All **historical related party transactions between the entities** [SpaceX, xAI, and X] **have been eliminated in consolidation.**"\n\nThis elimination means that any commercial, licensing, support, or other transactions that occurred between SpaceX, xAI, and X prior to the Mergers are **not visible** in the recast consolidated financial statements. Investors therefore cannot assess the volume, pricing, or economic significance of pre-merger intercompany dealings among these entities.\n\n## 11. Related Party Transactions with Tesla and Other Affiliates (Not Eliminated)\n\nBy contrast, transactions with **Tesla** (affiliated through Elon Musk\'s ~20% ownership and CEO role) and **The Boring Company** are disclosed because those entities are **not part of the consolidated group**. Key disclosed amounts include:\n\n**SpaceX–Tesla transactions (goods and services obtained from Tesla):**\n| Period | Amount |\n|---|---|\n| 2023 | $11 million |\n| 2024 | $4 million |\n| 2025 | $144 million |\n| Jan 1–Feb 28, 2026 | $0.2 million |\n\n**xAI–Tesla transactions (goods and services obtained from Tesla):**\n| Period | Amount |\n|---|---|\n| 2024 | $191 million |\n| 2025 | $506 million |\n| Jan 1–Feb 28, 2026 | $34 million |\n\n**xAI–Tesla revenue recognized by xAI:**\n| Period | Amount |\n|---|---|\n| 2025 | $2 million |\n| Jan 1–Feb 28, 2026 | $0.4 million |\n\n**X Holdings–Tesla advertising purchases on X:**\n| Period | Amount |\n|---|---|\n| 2024 | $0.5 million |\n| 2025 | $4 million |\n| Jan 1–Feb 28, 2026 | $0 |\n\n**Aircraft usage (SpaceX invoicing Tesla for Musk/Tesla personnel travel):**\n| Period | Amount |\n|---|---|\n| 2023 | $1 million |\n| 2024 | $1 million |\n| 2025 | $2 million |\n| Jan 1–Feb 28, 2026 | $0 |\n\n**The Boring Company lease:** In 2024, X entered into a lease for office space with a subsidiary owned by The Boring Company.\n\nAll Tesla transactions were described as being conducted on terms **"no less favorable to SpaceX than those generally available to unaffiliated third parties under similar circumstances."**\n\n## 12. Forward-Looking Statement and Risk Factor Cross-References\n\nThe prospectus repeatedly directs readers to the **"Risk Factors"** and **"Cautionary Statement Regarding Forward-Looking Statements"** sections, noting that actual results could differ materially from those described in or implied by forward-looking statements. The summary historical data is explicitly stated to be **not indicative** of future results.\n\n## Summary of Key Cautions\n\n| Caution | Disclosure |\n|---|---|\n| Historical data not indicative of future results | Explicitly stated in summary preamble |\n| Change in reporting entity | Explicitly identified; affects comparability |\n| No standalone xAI or X financials | "Separate financial statements of xAI and X are not provided" |\n| Intercompany transactions eliminated | All historical related party transactions between SpaceX, xAI, and X eliminated |\n| Segment realignment | New three-segment structure effective Q1 2026; prior periods conformed |\n| AI segment integration risk | "Recently formed, still being integrated...subject to integration, execution, competitive and operational risks" |\n| xAI preferred stock not retrospectively converted | Creates equity presentation discontinuity |\n| No new goodwill or intangibles recorded | Common-control accounting at historical carrying amounts |\n| Summary data qualified in its entirety | Not intended to replace full consolidated financial statements |',
